   <head>Lear on the Heath (from King Lear III.ii.1-9) </head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="blank verse">
     <l n="1" met="++-+-+++">Blow, winds, and crack your cheeks. Rage, blow.</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+-+-+-+-+">You cataracts and hurricanoes, spout</l>
     <l n="3" met="+--+-+-+-+">Till you have drenched our steeples, drowned the cocks.</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+--++-+-+-">You sulph'rous and thought-executing fires,</l>
     <l n="5" met="++--++-+-+">Vaunt-couriers of oak-cleaving thunderbolts,</l>
     <l n="6" met="+-++-+++-+-">Singe my white head. And thou, all-shaking thunder,</l>
     <l n="7" met="++-+-+--+-+">Strike flat the thick rotundity of the world,</l>
     <l n="8" met="++-+++-+-+">Crack Nature's moulds, all germains spill at once,</l>
     <l n="9" met="-+-+-+">That makes ingrateful man.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
